I"ï<h4><u><b> Javascript Variables </b></u></h4>

<ol>
  <li>Variable, rw(read/write)
    <ul>
      <li>variable declaration: let (added in ES6)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ol>
<pre>
    let name = 'genie';
    console.log(name);
    name = 'hello';
    console.log(name);
</pre>

<ul>
  <li>var : DO NOT EVER USE THIS!</li>
  <li>
    <ol>
      <li>It causes â€˜HOISTINGâ€™ which means â€˜pulling the declaration to the top.â€™; it results in a situation where variables can be used before their declarations and hence a spaggetti code.</li>
    </ol>
  </li>
  <li>
    <ol>
      <li>ignores block scope</li>
    </ol>
  </li>
</ul>
<pre>
    age = 4;
    var age;
</pre>

<ol>
  <li>Block scope</li>
</ol>
<pre>
    let globalName = "globalNm";
    {
        let name = 'localNm';
        console.log(name);
        name = 'hello';
        console.log(name);
        console.log(globalName);
    }
    console.log(name); // This prints nothing for its declaration is inside the scope.
    console.log(globalName);
</pre>

<ol>
  <li>Constant, r(read only)
    <ul>
      <li>use const whenever possible.</li>
      <li>only use let if the variable needs to change.</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ol>
<pre>
    const dayInWeek = 7;
</pre>

